Chapter 8 Regression Trees and Rule-Based Models

This is a tidymodels implementation of the code in Chapter 8 of Applied Predictive Modeling by Max Kuhn and Kjell Johnson1. I have already implemented all code and models from this chapter using mainly the caret package in a separate notebook, APM_8.Rmd. In that notebook I used the solTrainXtrans data set as the training data. This data set has already had a transformation applied to it (Box-Cox). In this notebook I have used the full data set (un-transformed) and did the Box-Cox transformation and data splitting myself using the appropriate recipe.

Load and Split Data

The tidymodels process has its own functions for splitting data. Combine the pre-split training and test data from the solubility data into one data frame, then use the tidymodels functions to split the data:

# Load data:
data(solubility)

# Combine the data sets (update the name of the outcome vectors to y so that they are the same).
# Also give the data frame a generic name.
df1 <- rbind(
  cbind(y = solTrainY, solTrainX), # training data
  cbind(y = solTestY, solTestX) # test data
)

# Split data:
set.seed(1)
splits <- initial_split(df1) # default prop is 3/4
df_train <- training(splits)
df_test <- testing((splits))

# Create folds for 10-fold cross-validation:
folds <- vfold_cv(df_train, v = 10)

8.1 Basic Regression Trees

CART trees

Training Data

Build a basic regression tree (CART) model and train using cross-validation:

# Recipe:
rec1 <-
  recipe(y ~ ., data = df_train) %>% 
  step_BoxCox(all_numeric(), -all_outcomes())

# Model:
cart_mod <-
  decision_tree(cost_complexity = tune()) %>% # `tree_depth` (30) and `min_n` (20) are left at their defaults (as was done with the `caret` model)
  set_engine("rpart") %>% 
  set_mode("regression")

# Workflow:
workflow1 <- 
  workflow() %>% 
  add_model(spec = cart_mod) %>% 
  add_recipe(recipe = rec1)

# Create a tuning grid with the same candidate values as the `caret` model (in `APM_8.R`): 
# Read in the grid of values used in the `caret` model (it was auto-generated by `caret` so hard to specify it separately here)
cp <- readRDS("/home/brian/R/dir/APM/chapter8/data/APM_8_cartTune.RDS")$results$cp
cart_grid <- expand.grid(cost_complexity = cp)

# Use `tune::tune_grid()` to combine the workflow and CV folds to fit the model on the training data:
## Read in cached results if available:
file1 <- "/home/brian/R/dir/APM/chapter8/data/cart_cv.RDS"
if (file.exists(file1)) {
  cart_cv <- readRDS(file1)
} else {
  cart_cv <-
    workflow1 %>%
    tune_grid(resamples = folds,
              grid = cart_grid,
              control = control_grid(save_pred = TRUE),
              metrics = metric_set(rmse, rsq))
  saveRDS(cart_cv, file1)
}

Plot CV results:

cart_cv %>% 
  collect_metrics() %>% 
  filter(.metric == "rmse") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(cost_complexity, mean)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_line() +
  scale_x_continuous(trans = "log10",
                     breaks = 10^seq(-2.5, -0.5, 0.5),
                     labels = str_c("10^", seq(-2.5, -0.5, 0.5))) +
  labs(y = "RMSE (CV)", title = "CART - RMSE profile")

The results are similar to the caret workflow and text (Fig. 8.5).

Select the best model and store the training error:

cart_best <- cart_cv %>% 
  select_best("rmse")

# Store the training error:
rmse_train <- cart_cv %>% 
  show_best("rmse") %>% 
  pluck("mean", 1)

Testing Data

Fit a model using all of the training data and apply it to the test data:

# Finalize the workflow by updating it to use the best model:
final_wf <- 
  workflow1 %>% 
  finalize_workflow(cart_best)

# This extracts the parameters in the final model (this code is clunky, could probably be made simpler):
wf <- final_wf %>% workflows::pull_workflow_spec()
cost_complexity <- wf$args$cost_complexity[2] %>% as.character() %>% as.numeric() %>% round(6)

  engine = "rpart",
  model = "CART",

  rmse_test = rmse_test,

8.3 Rule-Based Methods

The tidymodels framework implements rule-based methods using the rules package. Im not sure how to implement the same rule-based method as discussed in the book. See https://rules.tidymodels.org/index.html for more.

8.4 Bagged Trees

The tidymodels framework implements bagged models via the baguette package.

Build a single bagged CART tree model for the solubility data (as in APM_8.Rmd I will only use one value for the number of samples. Based on the docs for baguette Im not sure its possible to tune for this number. If a grid of values is required a loop would be needed.)

Training Data

I will use the same preprocessing recipe as the CART tree model (rec1):

# Model:
times1 <- 50 # 50 ensemble members
bag_tree_mod <-
  bag_tree() %>% # parameters are left at the default
  set_engine("rpart", times = times1) %>% # 50 ensemble members
  set_mode("regression") 

# Workflow:
workflow4 <- 
  workflow() %>% 
  add_model(spec = bag_tree_mod) %>% 
  add_recipe(recipe = rec1)

# Fit the model:
## Use `fit_resamples()` to fit the data using CV (no tuning grid required here).
## Read in cached results if available:
file1 <- "/home/brian/R/dir/APM/chapter8/data/bag_tree_fit.RDS"
if (file.exists(file1)) {
  bag_tree_fit <- readRDS(file1)
} else {
  bag_tree_fit <-
    workflow4 %>%
    fit_resamples(folds)
  saveRDS(bag_tree_fit, file1)
}

Use tune::collect_metrics() to evaluate the model:

collect_metrics(bag_tree_fit)

There is only one value for each metric, which is the training error estimated via 10-fold cross-validation (which itself is the mean of 10 values).

Store the training error:

rmse_train <- bag_tree_fit %>% 
  show_best("rmse") %>% 
  pluck("mean", 1)

Testing Data

Fit the final model using all of the training data and evaluate using the test data:

bag_tree_fit_final <- 
  workflow4 %>% 
  last_fit(splits)
  
# Store the test error:
rmse_test <- bag_tree_fit_final %>% 
  collect_metrics() %>% 
  filter(.metric == "rmse") %>% 
  pluck(".estimate")
rmse_test
[1] 0.6719

Store the training and test RMSE values and parameters:

RMSE_TM <- rbind(RMSE_TM,
                 c(framework = "tidymodels",
                   engine = "rpart",
                   model = "Bagged CART",
                   rmse_train = rmse_train,
                   rmse_test = rmse_test,
                   parameters = str_interp("times: ${times1}")))

8.5 Random Forests

The text implements random forests using CV and OOB estimates for evaluation of the models. They use CART trees and conditional inference trees. Since conditional inference trees arent implemented in tidymodels I will only implement CART tree models using both of the resampling methods.

First, a random forest with CART trees and 10-fold CV. Then a random forest with CART trees using OOB estimates.

Random Forest with CART trees and 10-fold CV

Training Data

# Model:
rf_mod <-
  rand_forest(mtry = tune()) %>%
  set_engine("randomForest") %>%
  set_mode("regression")

# Workflow:
workflow5 <- 
  workflow() %>% 
  add_model(spec = rf_mod) %>% 
  add_recipe(recipe = rec1)

# Create a tuning grid with the same candidate values as the `caret` model (in `APM_8.R`): 
rf_grid <- data.frame(mtry = floor(seq(10, ncol(solTrainX), length = 10)))

# Use `tune::tune_grid()` to combine the workflow and CV folds to fit the model on the training data:
## Read in cached results if available:
file1 <- "/home/brian/R/dir/APM/chapter8/data/rf_cv.RDS"
if (file.exists(file1)) {
  rf_cv <- readRDS(file1)
} else {
  rf_cv <-
    workflow5 %>%
    tune_grid(resamples = folds,
              grid = rf_grid,
              control = control_grid(save_pred = TRUE),
              metrics = metric_set(rmse, rsq))
  saveRDS(rf_cv, file1)
}

Plot CV results:

rf_cv %>% 
  collect_metrics() %>% 
  filter(.metric == "rmse") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(mtry, mean)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_line() +
  labs(y = "RMSE (CV)", title = "Random Forest with CART Trees - Cross-Validated RMSE profile")

Random Forest with CART trees and OOB estimation

The caret package uses 25 bootstrap samples by default, which is what I used in APM_8.Rmd. I will also use the same here.

# Bootstrap samples:
bootstrap_samples <- bootstraps(df_train, times = 25)

# Use `tune::tune_grid()` to combine the workflow and CV folds to fit the model on the training data:

8.6 Boosting

Training Data

# Model:
# tidymodels doesn't offer the gbm package. I am using xgboost instead. These are the equivalent parameters:
# interaction.depth = tree_depth; n.trees = trees; shrinkage = eta.
# n.minobsinnode from gbm is equivalent to min_n, but both of these are integers while the xgboost equivalent
# called min_child_weight is a real number (weight). I will leave this at the default for now.
boost_mod <-
  boost_tree(tree_depth = tune(), trees = tune(), learn_rate = tune()) %>%
  set_engine("xgboost") %>%
  set_mode("regression")

# Workflow:
workflow6 <- 
  workflow() %>% 
  add_model(spec = boost_mod) %>% 
  add_recipe(recipe = rec1)

# Create a tuning grid with the same candidate values as the `caret` model (in `APM_8.R`): 
boost_grid <- expand.grid(tree_depth = seq(1, 7, by = 2),
                          trees = seq(100, 1000, by = 50),
                          learn_rate = c(0.01, 0.1))

# Use `tune::tune_grid()` to combine the workflow and CV folds to fit the model on the training data:
## Read in cached results if available:
file1 <- "/home/brian/R/dir/APM/chapter8/data/boost_cv.RDS"
if (file.exists(file1)) {
  boost_cv <- readRDS(file1)
} else {
  boost_cv <-
    workflow6 %>%
    tune_grid(resamples = folds,
              grid = boost_grid,
              control = control_grid(save_pred = TRUE),
              metrics = metric_set(rmse, rsq))
  saveRDS(boost_cv, file1)
}

Plot metrics:

boost_cv %>% 
  collect_metrics() %>% 
  filter(.metric == "rmse") %>% 
  mutate(tree_depth = factor(tree_depth),
         learn_rate = factor(learn_rate)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(trees, mean, color = tree_depth)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_line() +
  facet_wrap(~learn_rate) +
  labs(y = "RMSE (CV)", title = "Boosted CART Trees - Cross-Validated RMSE profile") +
  theme(legend.position = "top")

The results are very similar to the caret workflow and text (Fig. 8.20).

# Fit the final model using all of the training data and evaluate using the test data:
boost_fit_final <- 
  final_wf %>%
  last_fit(splits) 

# Store test error:
rmse_test <- boost_fit_final %>% 
  collect_metrics() %>% 
  filter(.metric == "rmse") %>% 
  pluck(".estimate")

Store the training and test RMSE values and parameters:

                 c(framework = "tidymodels",
                   engine = "xgboost",
                   model = "Boosted CART Trees",
                   rmse_train = rmse_train,
                   rmse_test = rmse_test,
                   parameters = str_interp("tree_depth: ${tree_depth}; trees: ${trees}; learn_rate: ${learn_rate}")))

8.7 Cubist

Training Data

# Model:
cubist_mod <-
  cubist_rules(committees = tune(), neighbors = tune()) %>%
  set_mode("regression")

# Workflow:
workflow7 <- 
  workflow() %>% 
  add_model(spec = cubist_mod) %>% 
  add_recipe(recipe = rec1)

# Create a tuning grid with the same candidate values as the `caret` model (in `APM_8.R`): 
cubist_grid <- expand.grid(committees = c(1:10, 20, 50, 75, 100), 
                           neighbors = c(0, 1, 5, 9))

# Use `tune::tune_grid()` to combine the workflow and CV folds to fit the model on the training data:
## Read in cached results if available:
file1 <- "/home/brian/R/dir/APM/chapter8/data/cubist_cv.RDS"
if (file.exists(file1)) {
  cubist_cv <- readRDS(file1)
} else {
  cubist_cv <-
    workflow7 %>%
    tune_grid(resamples = folds,
              grid = cubist_grid,
              control = control_grid(save_pred = TRUE),
              metrics = metric_set(rmse, rsq))
  saveRDS(cubist_cv, file1)
}

Plot metrics:

cubist_cv %>% 
  collect_metrics() %>% 
  filter(.metric == "rmse") %>% 
  mutate(neighbors = factor(neighbors)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(committees, mean, color = neighbors)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_line() +
  labs(y = "RMSE (CV)", title = "Cubist - Cross-Validated RMSE profile") +
  theme(legend.position = "top")

The results are very similar to the caret workflow and text (Fig. 8.22).
